a2=A.y("Challenges",s.w,c8,c8)
a0=A.w(c8,a0,c8)
a3=A.y("There is growing demand for the broader public to participate in the development of stories, be it in theater, fanfiction or choose-your-own-adventure movies and video games. Hence we focused on developing a one-act interactive opera, along an online interaction environment.\nAllowing the audience to impact the story through natural interactions that were thematically compelling. \nEngaging the public in a conversation around the issues of tolerance, gender identity, bullying, disability and mental health.",A.v(c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8),c8,c8)
a4=s.y
a5=A.w(c8,a4,c8)
a6=A.y("Process",s.w,c8,c8)
a7=A.w(c8,a4,c8)
a8=A.y("Participative performance",s.x,c8,c8)
a4=A.w(c8,a4,c8)
a9=A.y("As the developer, I was tasked with bringing together the libretto, soundtrack, stage, characters and animations (previously developed by the production team) into an augmented virtuality (VR experiences enhanced with live elements) opera in Unity3D.   To enhance the feeling of immersion and engagement of the audience/participants, the two main presenters sang and declared their lines live in sync with the execution of the opera.  \n\nWe explored different alternatives to interaction technologies, including AR elements, a \u2018breathing belt\u2019 and a microphone for the audience. I used the Vuforia plugin to manage AR elements, allowing the participants to impose their face over the face of the character of their choosing. I modified a  belt with a stretch sensor that sampled the expansion of the diaphragm to describe the breathing cycle of the user. In the end, we decided to use a microphone instead for controlling interactions as it provided a more robust signal, was portable and did not require the participants to wear any device. \n\nTo give participants a constant feedback of their interaction in a way that made sense in the story, the amplitude of audio signal coming from the audience microphone governed the behavior of the flora and fauna on the scene (they produce wind proportional to the volume of the microphone, while their color depended on the pitch of the sound).\n\nFinally, when the final scene came, the audience could support the main character by singing along. In terms of the script, the main character was being bullied into falling from the edge of a cliff. Only if the flora and fauna of the scene produced enough wind (the audience sang loud enough), the wind would support the main character's newly formed wings and deliver her safely.\n\nDuring the discussions following public presentations, the desire of the audience to become more immersed became evident. Hence, I created a multiplayer VR (360~ interface and google cardboard viewer interface) version of the opera. Processing the game scripts, audio processing and rendering of the scene was not possible in real-time on mobile devices. My solution was to pre-record a 360 video of the complete opera without the interactive elements, then import the video in a new project and add the interactive elements and a server authoritative networking system. This way, participants could experience a 360 VR  interactive experience of the opera and collaborate towards supporting the main character at the ending of the opera.",A.v(c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8),c8,c8)
b0=s.y
b1=A.w(c8,b0,c8)
b2=A.y("Cocreation environment",s.x,c8,c8)
b0=A.w(c8,b0,c8)
b3=A.y("Our multiplayer online co-creation environment was designed to engage the audience of the opera in collaborative creation of content and social interactions before and after the performance. Participants could chat and meet at four different stations in the virtual environment, and collect different medallions to receive an oracle reading. \n\nThe dance station allowed the users to time the spawn of opera dancers to form a group choreography that interacted with that of the other players.\nThe sound station allowed the participants to grow the flora of the opera, which would extract the notes of the user-generated sound and play back a piano melody based on it. Each flora will play back its melody when a player collides with it, so by exploring the station and colliding with the collective flora, players could orchestrate a variety of co-created songs. \nThe breathing station would provide an opportunity for players to sync their breathing or singing with that of others. The fauna of the station detects the sound of the microphone of all the players in the area and plays a melody whenever it is loud enough. If the local player is singing/exhaling/whistling at the same time as the rest of the players, his fauna will play a harmonious melody, otherwise, the melody will be dissonant. \nThe fan-fiction station is the least developed so far. Players could spawn a \u2018portal\u2019 where participants could write texts and upload a cover image to be displayed in the portal. \n\nI deployed a headless server built in a linux machine to manage the networking aspect of the interface. This preliminary built was stable up to 20 simultaneous players, with performance sharply dropping after 40 players.",A.v(c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8),c8,c8)
b4=s.y
b5=A.w(c8,b4,c8)
b6=A.y("Reflection",s.w,c8,c8)
b4=A.w(c8,b4,c8)
b7=A.y("Interacting through natural movements or sounds in virtual environments can increase the feeling of immersion. \n\nParticipatory presentations can engage people in the discussion around sensitive topics like diversity and inclusion. \n\nCocreation environments could influence the development of artistic works, support \u2018world building\u2019 in literary universes, and support community interactions around a topic. \n\nFor small audiences, augmented virtuality operas are a feasible product where another medium of production might be prohibitively expensive. \n\nInfluencing the behavior of the flora and fauna of the environment can be a non intrusive way of engaging audiences and subtly affecting the ending of the story. ",A.v(c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8,c8),c8,c8)
